                        <bindingDesc>
                          <binding contemporary="partly" xml:id="binding">
                            <decoNote xml:id="b1">
                              Ethiopic bookbinding with wooden boards and quarter leather cover.
                            </decoNote>
                            <decoNote xml:id="b2" type="bindingMaterial">
                           <material key="wood"/>
                           <material key="leather"/>
                        </decoNote>
                            <decoNote xml:id="b3" type="Boards">
                              The upper board is made of a dark brown wood. The lower board is composed by two pieces of wood held together with vegetal thread passing through
                              holes created on both sides. The external half is made of the same kind of wood of the upper board but the grain is horizontal.
                              The inner half is made by a brown-reddish wood. Probably both boards are not original and they have been reused.
                            </decoNote>
                            <decoNote xml:id="b4" type="Cover">
                              A quarter cover made of yellowish-brown leather is glued onto the spine.
                              It is decorated with <term key="tripleStraightLine" ana="#tripleStraightLine"/> forming six rectangular frames in which they cross each other diagonally.
                              At intersections <term key="doubleCircle" ana="#doubleCircle">double circles</term> are found.
                              The spine is decorated with triple straight lines crossing each other diagonally.</decoNote>
                            <decoNote xml:id="b5" type="Endbands" color="yellow">
                              <term key="slitBraid" ana="#slitBraid">Slit-braid</term> endbands are present and sewn to the bookblock with a thread of animal origin.
                              The headband is sewn starting from the upper board, linking the braid to the first sewing station while the tailband
                              is sewn starting from the lower board, linking the braid to the last sewing station. The sewing ends inside the closest quire.
                            </decoNote>
                            <decoNote xml:id="b6" type="SewingStations">4</decoNote>
                            <decoNote xml:id="b7">
                              The sewing is a chain-stitch on four sewing stations (two pairs).
                              Since the sewing has been repaired is not possible to individuate the pattern.
                            </decoNote>
                            <decoNote xml:id="b11" type="EndLeaves">
                              The first bifolio has a protective function.
                            </decoNote>
                          </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
